  "prompt": "What are good examples of websites built using Adobe ColdFusion?",
  "response": "Adobe ColdFusion is a robust web application development platform that's been used by various organizations to build dynamic and scalable websites. While many large-scale public websites may not prominently disclose their underlying technologies, several notable examples and types of organizations are known to utilize ColdFusion:\n\n1. **Government Websites:**\n   - **U.S. Department of Education:** Some portals and services within the department leverage ColdFusion for dynamic content delivery and data management.\n   - **State Government Portals:** Various state-level government websites use ColdFusion for their web applications, offering services ranging from public records access to online form submissions.\n\n2. **Educational Institutions:**\n   - **Universities and Colleges:** Many higher education institutions use ColdFusion for their internal portals, course management systems, and public-facing websites to handle registration, information dissemination, and more.\n\n3. **Enterprise and Financial Services:**\n   - **Insurance Companies:** Several insurance firms utilize ColdFusion for customer portals, policy management systems, and internal applications.\n   - **Financial Institutions:** Some banks and financial services companies employ ColdFusion to manage online banking platforms, transactional systems, and secure data processing applications.\n\n4. **Non-Profit Organizations:**\n   - **Charitable Organizations:** Non-profits often use ColdFusion to build websites that handle donations, event registrations, volunteer management, and informational content.\n\n5. **E-commerce Platforms:**\n   - **Online Retailers:** Certain e-commerce websites use ColdFusion for managing product catalogs, shopping carts, payment processing, and customer relationship management.\n\n6. **Healthcare Providers:**\n   - **Hospitals and Clinics:** Healthcare websites built with ColdFusion may offer patient portals, appointment scheduling, medical records access, and information resources.\n\n7. **Media and Publishing:**\n   - **News Outlets and Magazines:** Some media organizations utilize ColdFusion to manage content publishing, user subscriptions, and interactive features on their websites.\n\n8. **Technology and Software Companies:**\n   - **Software Vendors:** Companies providing software solutions may use ColdFusion for their product websites, support portals, and customer engagement platforms.\n\n**Notable Examples:**\n- **Adobe\u2019s Own Websites:** Naturally, Adobe leverages ColdFusion for some of its web platforms and services.\n- **Dell:** At certain points, Dell has used ColdFusion in parts of their web infrastructure, particularly for internal tools and specific applications.\n\n**Showcases and Case Studies:**\nFor more specific examples, Adobe maintains a [ColdFusion Showcase](https://coldfusion.adobe.com/showcase/) where various organizations highlight how they've utilized ColdFusion in their projects. This resource provides detailed case studies and examples across different industries, demonstrating the versatility and capabilities of Adobe ColdFusion in real-world applications.\n\n**Conclusion:**\nWhile Adobe ColdFusion may not be as widely publicized as some modern frameworks like Node.js or Django, it remains a powerful tool for building dynamic, secure, and scalable web applications, particularly within enterprise, governmental, and specialized sectors. For organizations considering ColdFusion, the platform offers extensive features and a supportive community, backed by Adobe's continued development and support.",
